1) Explain the purpose of non-parameterized methods in Java. When would you prefer using them?
-->A non-parameterized method is a method that does not take any input values (parameters).

    Purpose:
    
    Used when no external input is required
    Performs fixed operations
    Improves code reusability and readability
    
    When to use:
    
    When logic does not depend on user input
    Example: printing a message, displaying menu, fixed calculations
    void displayMessage() {
        System.out.println("Welcome to Java");
    }


2) Can a non-parameterized method return different data types? Demonstrate with examples.
-->Yes, a non-parameterized method can return any data type, but one method returns only one type at a time.
    
    Examples:
    
    int getNumber() {
        return 10;
    }
    
    String getMessage() {
        return "Hello";
    }
    
    boolean isValid() {
        return true;
    }
    
    👉 Each method has no parameters, but returns different data types



3) Can a non-parameterized method access instance variables and static variables? Explain.
-->Yes.

    Explanation:
    
    It can access instance variables (if it's an instance method)
    It can access static variables directly
    class Demo {
        int x = 10;           // instance variable
        static int y = 20;    // static variable
    
        void show() {
            System.out.println(x); // instance variable
            System.out.println(y); // static variable
        }
    }



4) Can a non-parameterized method call another method that has parameters? Explain with an example.
-->Yes.

    Explanation:
    A non-parameterized method can call another method by passing values manually.
    
    class Demo {
        void display() {
            add(5, 3); // calling parameterized method
        }
    
        void add(int a, int b) {
            System.out.println(a + b);
        }
    }



5) What happens if you call a non-parameterized instance method before creating an object?
-->It will cause a compile-time error.

Reason:
Instance methods belong to objects, so you must create an object before calling them.

class Demo {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        show(); // ❌ ERROR
    }
}

Correct way:

Demo obj = new Demo();
obj.show(); // ✅ Correct

